WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:04.080
Judith Butler might be the most misunderstood philosopher in the world,

00:04.080 --> 00:07.280
so I decided to read as much of their work as I could in one month.

00:07.280 --> 00:11.360
Actually, I read it in like four months, but YouTube videos need narrative now.

00:11.360 --> 00:16.160
Butler has been writing for over 40 years about a lot of things, including gender.

00:16.160 --> 00:19.920
If you've ever heard the idea that gender is performative, that's them.

00:19.920 --> 00:22.800
Their work has also been the subject of huge backlash,

00:22.800 --> 00:27.600
like in 2017, protesters in Brazil burned an effigy of Judith Butler.

00:27.680 --> 00:29.840
Philosophy doesn't usually get that spicy.

00:29.840 --> 00:32.560
I must have missed the effigy making class during my degree.

00:32.560 --> 00:35.520
Interestingly, the people with the strongest reactions to Butler

00:35.520 --> 00:38.560
often haven't understood or even read their work,

00:38.560 --> 00:41.600
and now they have a new book about the backlash.

00:41.600 --> 00:43.840
Who's Afraid of Gender?

00:43.840 --> 00:47.360
I've deliberately filmed the bulk of this video on a white void background

00:47.360 --> 00:48.960
with minimal costumes.

00:48.960 --> 00:51.760
Kind of an old-fashioned style on YouTube these days,

00:51.760 --> 00:55.760
but I wanted to get across the idea that as controversial as this stuff might be,

00:55.760 --> 00:56.880
there's nothing hidden.

00:56.880 --> 00:59.360
You're not committing yourself to anything by hearing it.

00:59.360 --> 01:03.120
It's just an invitation to listen and consider a different point of view.

01:03.120 --> 01:06.240
And really, that's a skill we could all do with practicing,

01:06.240 --> 01:10.000
because this philosophy has huge real-world implications.

01:10.000 --> 01:12.240
I was inspired to take this research journey

01:12.240 --> 01:14.800
when I read this article in The Washington Post.

01:14.800 --> 01:17.840
Students from E.C. Glass High School in Lynchburg, Virginia,

01:17.840 --> 01:20.240
applied for a grant from It Gets Better,

01:20.240 --> 01:22.960
a non-profit dedicated to kids' mental health.

01:22.960 --> 01:24.080
And they got it.

01:24.080 --> 01:27.920
They were awarded $10,000 to put a chill-out room in their school,

01:27.920 --> 01:31.520
