04:10.880 --> 04:12.320
Let's talk about Fem boys.

04:13.520 --> 04:15.920
I began at the beginning.

04:15.920 --> 04:17.920
Butler's 1988 paper,

04:17.920 --> 04:20.640
Performative Acts and Gender Constitution,

04:20.640 --> 04:23.040
one of the first things they ever wrote.

04:23.040 --> 04:24.880
And right up top, we should acknowledge,

04:24.880 --> 04:28.160
Butler's academic writing can sometimes be pretty difficult.

04:28.160 --> 04:29.120
And that's fair enough.

04:29.680 --> 04:31.520
Gender is a difficult subject.

04:32.320 --> 04:33.840
Mine took me two attempts.

04:33.840 --> 04:37.120
What made it click for me is it reminded me of a friend

04:37.840 --> 04:40.160
who will call F.

04:41.680 --> 04:45.600
F is very cool, clever and funny.

04:45.600 --> 04:47.680
And unpretentious, the kind of person who turns up

04:47.680 --> 04:49.440
to a fancy restaurant wearing a trucker hat.

04:50.240 --> 04:51.920
F is also a Fem boy.

04:52.560 --> 04:54.320
Fem boys take on attributes

04:54.320 --> 04:56.000
that are typically considered feminine,

04:56.000 --> 04:59.040
but they are not themselves women, usually.

04:59.600 --> 05:02.800
Fem boy is also a genre of online content.

05:02.800 --> 05:04.480
F dresses up like a girl

05:04.480 --> 05:06.480
and streams themselves playing video games.

05:06.480 --> 05:11.680
When I first met F, I wondered, is Fem boy a gender?

05:12.560 --> 05:15.840
Well, it's less a thing that you are

05:15.840 --> 05:19.040
and more a thing that you do like a job.

05:19.680 --> 05:22.320
And interestingly, because the Fem boy aesthetic

05:22.320 --> 05:24.800
is so shaped by online content,

05:24.800 --> 05:28.240
to do Fem boy in a way that other people will recognize

05:28.240 --> 05:30.720
requires you to adopt certain behaviors

05:30.720 --> 05:32.400
and stylized practices

05:32.400 --> 05:35.040
whose meaning is not determined by you.

05:35.680 --> 05:38.240
You can't choose what the trends are,

05:38.240 --> 05:41.520
what styles of makeup or dress signal Fem boy.

05:41.840 --> 05:44.080
You've got to learn them and do them

05:44.080 --> 05:45.920
if you want to be seen that way.

05:45.920 --> 05:48.000
And F works pretty hard at that.

05:48.000 --> 05:49.360
If you're very clever,

05:49.360 --> 05:51.920
you'll already have guessed where this is going.

05:52.800 --> 05:57.200
According to Butler, all gender works that way.

05:58.000 --> 06:00.800
In this paper, they say that gender is a thing

06:00.800 --> 06:05.120
we do through repeated, stylized acts.

06:05.120 --> 06:08.480
Not a property, but an embodied event.

06:09.280 --> 06:12.400
Those acts get their meaning from a social world.

06:12.400 --> 06:16.960
So in a way, gender is also a thing that is done to us.

06:16.960 --> 06:19.360
Gender is in no way a stable identity

06:19.360 --> 06:21.920
or locus of agency from which various acts proceed.

06:22.560 --> 06:26.720
Rather, it's an identity tenuously constituted in time,

06:26.720 --> 06:30.640
an identity instituted through a stylized repetition of acts.

06:31.280 --> 06:34.400
Further, gender is instituted through a stylization of the body

06:34.400 --> 06:36.880
and hence must be understood as the mundane way

06:36.880 --> 06:39.280
in which bodily gestures, movements and enactments

06:39.280 --> 06:42.960
of various kinds constitute the illusion of an abiding gendered self.

06:43.520 --> 06:44.720
You're ridiculous.

06:44.720 --> 06:46.240
Says discount Tom Hiddleston.

06:46.240 --> 06:48.240
Your face doesn't look like me anymore.

06:48.240 --> 06:50.720
Did you get plastic surgery on my face?

06:50.720 --> 06:52.320
Well, there's no plastic in me, babes.

06:52.320 --> 06:53.200
I'm all natural.

06:53.200 --> 06:55.120
Artificial surgery makes you natural, does it?

06:56.240 --> 07:00.480
At first glance, Butler's ideas seemed a little strange to me

07:00.480 --> 07:03.920
because we often talk as if gender is an inner truth.

07:03.920 --> 07:07.440
For example, when people change gender and come out,

07:07.440 --> 07:12.480
we're often said to be living authentically or being true to ourselves.

07:12.480 --> 07:17.680
Even the term coming out implies that there was an authentic self before who was hidden.

07:17.680 --> 07:21.520
But according to Butler, there might be no such thing.

07:22.320 --> 07:28.000
It's not that I exist and then I choose to perform gender in ways that you will recognize.

07:28.000 --> 07:32.480
I can't even form a concept of I without using gendered language

07:32.480 --> 07:36.800
and stylized practices whose meaning exists prior to me.

07:37.600 --> 07:42.240
Gender is one of the ways that human subjects come into existence.

07:42.240 --> 07:48.960
The technical term here is subjectification, and that process happens publicly.

07:49.840 --> 07:54.480
Gender creates the illusion of a private self which exists before all of that,

07:54.480 --> 07:56.960
but this is just an illusion.

07:56.960 --> 07:59.840
If a tree falls in the forest and nobody's around to hear it,

08:00.640 --> 08:02.560
it has no pronouns.

08:02.560 --> 08:08.160
Herein lies the distinction between performative and performance,

08:08.160 --> 08:09.360
which are often mixed up.

08:10.160 --> 08:13.120
When people say gender is a performance,

08:13.120 --> 08:16.160
they mean that people exist first without gender,

08:16.160 --> 08:20.240
and then they put on costumes or makeup or wigs the way that an actor does.

08:20.240 --> 08:22.800
But that's not what Butler is saying.

08:23.680 --> 08:27.040
Performative is a technical philosophy term

08:27.040 --> 08:31.440
for when you say something and by saying it, you also do it.

08:31.440 --> 08:37.120
For example, if you say I promise, you say the words and you make a promise.

08:37.120 --> 08:41.840
If a judge says I sentence you, they say it and they do it.

08:42.480 --> 08:47.040
When Butler says that gender is performative, they mean it that way.

08:47.040 --> 08:54.960
You do it and you make it so, and indeed by doing it, you are made so.

08:54.960 --> 08:57.600
And people have made fun of Butler for this idea.

08:57.600 --> 09:00.400
I've seen people say, oh, Judith Butler says,

09:00.400 --> 09:03.120
you can just choose to be any gender you want.

09:03.120 --> 09:07.360
Oh, I men can choose to be women and women can choose to be baboons

09:07.360 --> 09:09.680
and I can choose to be an attack helicopter.

09:09.680 --> 09:11.280
Ha ha, how silly.

09:11.280 --> 09:13.360
But when I actually read their work,

09:13.360 --> 09:16.000
I realized that's not what they're saying at all.

09:16.800 --> 09:22.640
Our very concept of ourselves as gendered subjects requires a social world.

09:22.720 --> 09:27.680
We depend on others for the recognition we need to become gendered subjects.

09:27.680 --> 09:31.600
We can still make some choices where whatever clothes or makeup you like,

09:32.160 --> 09:37.280
but the meaning of those things is not within our soul control.

09:37.280 --> 09:41.520
People have been making jokes like that about Butler for decades,

09:41.520 --> 09:48.560
even though they address this misunderstanding in their first paper, in the first paragraph.

09:49.520 --> 09:55.040
Almost like the people mocking them aren't really listening.

09:59.760 --> 10:04.560
There is no volitional subject behind the mime who decides, as it were,

10:04.560 --> 10:06.000
which gender it will be today.

10:06.640 --> 10:11.280
On the contrary, the very possibility of becoming a viable subject

10:11.280 --> 10:15.040
requires that a certain gender mime be already underway.

10:15.040 --> 10:17.360
I didn't come back here to argue with you, I'm trying to help.

10:17.360 --> 10:18.720
I don't believe it, it's a trick.

10:19.600 --> 10:20.960
You were born in your castle.

10:20.960 --> 10:22.560
Your favourite fruit is Chinese.

10:22.560 --> 10:24.400
Your first crush was named Flossy.

10:24.400 --> 10:27.360
No, no, no, you could have tortured me and got in that information.

10:27.360 --> 10:27.680
What?

10:27.680 --> 10:30.080
Well, I don't know, you could have gotten it out on me somehow in the future.

10:30.080 --> 10:33.680
Just listen to me, we're the same height, we have the same eyes.

10:33.680 --> 10:35.440
Your body's completely different.

10:35.440 --> 10:37.200
Yes, that's the point.

10:37.200 --> 10:39.200
Human bodies can't change that much.

10:39.200 --> 10:39.680
We can!

10:39.680 --> 10:42.400
Even if you are, even if you are, even if you are, even if you are.

10:42.400 --> 10:44.320
Let's talk about Kristen Stewart.

10:44.320 --> 10:49.040
Next on my reading list was Butler's famous 1990 book Gender Trouble.

10:49.040 --> 10:52.640
But it's pretty tough and technical, so we could use a bit of a run-up.

10:52.640 --> 10:55.040
We can actually start with this.

10:55.920 --> 11:00.560
In March 2024, actor Kristen Stewart appeared on the cover of Rolling Stone, looking…

11:04.720 --> 11:07.120
In the interview, Stewart said,

11:07.120 --> 11:11.920
I want to do the gayest f***ing thing you've ever seen in your life.

11:12.800 --> 11:20.480
If I could grow a little mustache, if I could grow a f***ing happy trail and unbutton my pants,

11:21.840 --> 11:22.800
I would.

11:22.800 --> 11:25.600
Later at the Berlin Film Festival, she added,

11:25.600 --> 11:31.200
The existence of a female body thrusting any type of sexuality at you that's not designed for

11:31.200 --> 11:37.440
or desired by exclusively cis straight males is something people are not super comfy with.

11:37.440 --> 11:39.600
And so I am really happy with it.

11:39.600 --> 11:41.280
I had a great time.

11:41.280 --> 11:45.520
A lot of people think that there's a difference between sex and gender.

11:46.240 --> 11:51.680
Sex is supposed to be the physical thing, some combination of genes or genitals or gametes,

11:51.680 --> 11:55.760
or maybe it's something in your brain, but it's there in the world.

11:55.760 --> 12:01.280
And gender is just what we do with it, or at least that's how the story goes.

12:01.280 --> 12:05.200
It might be helpful to know something of the history of that idea.

12:05.840 --> 12:09.360
For millennia, male-dominated societies exploited women

12:09.360 --> 12:12.960
and justified it by claiming that we are naturally inferior.

12:12.960 --> 12:16.480
From Greek and Roman philosophers saying that women can't be educated,

12:16.480 --> 12:20.480
to Victorian doctors saying that we are too emotional to vote, to today.

12:20.480 --> 12:26.880
Some people still say women are by nature not equipped to live as equal members of society.

12:26.880 --> 12:28.720
Oh, she could never lead a nation.

12:28.720 --> 12:30.800
What if she got her period and started a war?

12:32.000 --> 12:35.600
Misogyny has consistently justified itself by appealing to

12:35.680 --> 12:39.520
facts about our bodies that are simply made up.

12:39.520 --> 12:42.800
If you'd like to know more about the history of this practice, then I really recommend

12:44.240 --> 12:48.320
The Once and Future Sex by historian Eleanor Yanagher.

12:48.320 --> 12:52.160
Into this context comes French philosopher Simone de Beauvoir,

12:52.160 --> 12:58.320
whose landmark book The Second Sex comes out in 1949 and opens with this sentence.

12:58.320 --> 13:01.920
One is not born, but rather becomes a woman.

13:01.920 --> 13:07.440
De Beauvoir challenges this history, saying that whilst there are facts about female biology,

13:08.000 --> 13:14.080
male-dominated society also makes a lot of stuff up and claims that the stuff it makes up is facts.

13:14.080 --> 13:19.680
The technical term here is naturalization, making something appear natural.

13:19.680 --> 13:22.080
For example, women are denied the vote?

13:22.080 --> 13:24.560
Well, it's not because we live in an unequal society,

13:24.560 --> 13:29.040
it's because the female brain just can't handle it because of biology.

13:29.040 --> 13:38.240
So, she says, one is born female, but woman is a socially constructed ideal of subordination,

13:38.240 --> 13:42.640
that we are encouraged to embrace and punished for defying.

13:42.640 --> 13:48.960
And then, in the 1980s, along come French philosophers Monique Wittig and Michel Foucault,

13:48.960 --> 13:54.640
who say this sex versus gender distinction is just another layer of control.

13:55.280 --> 14:02.880
De Beauvoir thinks that woman is an oppressive social construct, but female somehow isn't?

14:04.320 --> 14:09.760
Human beings are 99.9% identical. Who does it serve to split hairs about the remaining 0.1%?

14:10.560 --> 14:15.200
Defining one half of the human species in terms of our capacity to carry babies and be fertile

14:15.200 --> 14:21.280
and straight and thereby participate in systems of property and inheritance overwhelmingly controlled

14:21.280 --> 14:28.080
by men? Does that sound like a natural distinction? Or does it sound like a political one?

14:28.080 --> 14:34.080
Wittig actually says that women should reject womanhood entirely by becoming lesbians,

14:34.080 --> 14:38.560
rejecting the patriarchal categories of both woman and female.

14:38.560 --> 14:44.720
Categories which she says only make sense inside the heterosexual matrix.

14:44.800 --> 14:51.840
Do not try and change sex. That's impossible. Instead, only try to realize the truth.

14:54.080 --> 14:59.440
There is no sex. We've been compelled in our bodies and in our minds to correspond

14:59.440 --> 15:03.520
feature by feature with the idea of nature that has been established for us,

15:03.520 --> 15:08.160
distorted to such an extent that our deformed body is what they call natural,

15:08.160 --> 15:13.040
what is supposed to exist as such before oppression, distorted to such an extent

15:13.040 --> 15:17.520
that in the end oppression seems to be a consequence of this nature within ourselves.

15:18.080 --> 15:23.440
By admitting that there is a natural division between women and men, we naturalize history.

15:23.440 --> 15:28.080
Not only do we naturalize history, but also consequently we naturalize the social phenomena

15:28.080 --> 15:34.160
which express our oppression, making change impossible. Lesbian is the only concept I know

15:34.160 --> 15:40.640
of which is beyond the categories of sex, woman and man, because the designated subject, lesbian,

15:40.640 --> 15:44.800
is not a woman, either economically or politically or ideologically.

15:45.520 --> 15:50.080
For what makes a woman is a specific social relation to a man, a relation that we have

15:50.080 --> 15:55.280
previously called servitude, a relation which implies personal and physical obligation as well

15:55.280 --> 16:00.080
as economic obligation, forced residence, domestic corvée, conjugal duties, unlimited production

16:00.080 --> 16:06.480
of children, etc. A relation which lesbians escape by refusing to become or stay heterosexual.

16:07.120 --> 16:11.120
I'm not sure that I personally agree with everything Wittig says, but it's a provocative

16:11.120 --> 16:17.760
thought, worth listening to, and in gender trouble, Butler thinks so too. They say we should

16:17.760 --> 16:24.640
question the idea that sex is a natural category. That might sound very out there, but just listen

16:24.640 --> 16:30.240
for a moment. Once upon a time, people believed that race was a natural category. They wrote

16:30.240 --> 16:35.120
scientific papers about it and measured people's skulls and took blood samples and they believed

16:35.120 --> 16:40.720
that it was real. Nowadays we know that race is a political grouping that was naturalized,

16:40.720 --> 16:46.720
made to look natural, in large part to justify slavery. And we also know that sex was a big

16:46.720 --> 16:53.520
part of that. Black women and white women were categorized very differently. So are you certain

16:54.080 --> 16:59.440
that the distinction between male and female is as secure as you've been told?

17:01.520 --> 17:02.400
Who told you that?

17:02.640 --> 17:06.960
Why did they tell you it?

17:09.040 --> 17:12.080
And who benefits from you continuing to believe it?

17:12.080 --> 17:13.920
You think that's pussy you're eating now?

17:13.920 --> 17:19.440
This is the artistic space that Christian Stewart's photo shoot is playing in. The

17:19.440 --> 17:26.560
piece and Stewart's comments engage in what Butler calls re-signification, giving a new

17:26.560 --> 17:32.800
meaning to something. In this case, Stewart's body. The question it poses is, what if this

17:33.520 --> 17:42.720
is also female? What does that tell us about the sense or non-sense of gendered categories?

17:42.720 --> 17:51.200
But if sex isn't real, then why did I go through all the trouble of changing mine?

17:51.600 --> 17:55.440
It's a blunt question, but it's not an unfair one.

17:56.320 --> 18:03.360
So when I finished gender trouble, I also read this, Whipping Girl by Julius Serrano. Serrano

18:03.360 --> 18:09.600
is a biologist. She believes in what she calls subconscious sex, something in the brain that

18:09.600 --> 18:14.960
expects the body to be a certain way. She thinks this would explain the existence of people like

18:14.960 --> 18:22.960
me and also her, whose gender just feels right. It's an interesting idea, and I think it gets

18:22.960 --> 18:30.480
to the heart of an intuition a lot of us have to go, look, like physical differences are there.

18:30.480 --> 18:34.480
We can see them. Some human beings can get pregnant and others can't. Like,

18:35.200 --> 18:40.080
is Butler really saying that all of that isn't real? But then I read the book again,

18:40.080 --> 18:46.400
and it turns out that's also a misunderstanding. Butler's not saying that the physical world

18:46.400 --> 18:50.720
isn't there or even that it's unknowable. They're just saying that whatever facts

18:50.720 --> 18:58.480
there might be about biological sex, we can only learn them and talk about them through gender.

